		<title>By: Gregg</title>
		<link>http://ngs.ics.uci.edu/milkshake-drunk-researcher-and-problem-solving/comment-page-1/#comment-3776</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Gregg]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 28 Jul 2010 01:23:25 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://ngs.ics.uci.edu/blog/?p=1279#comment-3776</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Often a fresh or different approach is best when solving a problem. A lot of times in college, I would read the chapter assigned and then intentionally look for another book by a different author on the same subject and get another view point. This was so helpful because, maybe this new angle of approach was just better for me. Not, that the second author was any better than the first one but, the example he stated had some consequence for me that just stuck in my mind. Answers to problems are not always were you look first, second or sometimes the last place you look. A fresh approach or a fresh mind is usually where the answer lies.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Often a fresh or different approach is best when solving a problem. A lot of times in college, I would read the chapter assigned and then intentionally look for another book by a different author on the same subject and get another view point. This was so helpful because, maybe this new angle of approach was just better for me. Not, that the second author was any better than the first one but, the example he stated had some consequence for me that just stuck in my mind. Answers to problems are not always were you look first, second or sometimes the last place you look. A fresh approach or a fresh mind is usually where the answer lies.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
